The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic from this year.
Possibly
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Here, however, something is missing – a virtual operator that forces the traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
The fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end, <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> also confirmed this, which noted that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the European Commission's latest steps in the regulation of roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that would really like to start the fight.
It may sound absurd, and here too we have three mobile networks and coverage far above 100%.
Mobile telephony operators, on the other hand, like to argue that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, has also often stressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network probably no longer has many possibilities. (By the way, it would probably be difficult to find other frequencies by now).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators that has led to a significant drop in prices, to which traditional operators would have to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar voices sounded in Britain as we did.
However, it has been shown that the place for such operators is there and that they can be truly successful.
After all, we do not have to go very far.
In February of this year we informed you about the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, to which in the Czech Republic, among other things, U:fon belongs.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to work effectively, that is, many fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry, i.e., relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world, virtual operators usually present themselves at a low cost, offer low-cost calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the narrower offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that cost at least half of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a pretty good move even betting on a target group not so long ago.
This operator is aiming to say so specifically about men.
“The real men choose the Mobilking operator they like and trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can claim a similar concept as in Poland.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators rely.
In addition, from the point of view of services it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, mobile network operators say
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not have many expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in other countries in our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokesman for the financial group Penta, told Mobile.cz.
So he indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are certainly not very favorable to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything because you do not create any potential competitors.
For some time he has not concealed his interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And first you do better it is.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already managed to make progress in the negotiations with some of them," said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will probably have it by the end of the year.
But for now, around its creation, an impenetrable wall of silence is erected.
“At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also rely on the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobil press spokesman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: “For now we have not noticed any commercial projects that are vital and beneficial to both, on which it is possible to continue to build.”
He adds: “On the T-Mobil network, a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this point, we will already have to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it can be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on achieving its own 3G license requests.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: “We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most producer.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Competent authorities - with accomplices
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The inconveniences surrounding the creation of U:fon testify that when operators hold on to something they know how to remarry on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was exerted against <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidence of public access information from <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for which you do not accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> commented: “The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has been little further enhanced with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on him and above all on his services."
However, the attitude of mobile operators is quite surprising the complete disinterest on the part of Czech regulators.
It is not only the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> that, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic – unlike Great Britain and other developed countries – has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, with regard to the whole problem has taken its typical position.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristian Chalupa, from the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS external relations section, in answer to our question.
Such a statement by representatives of operators may not be surprising.
Instead, on the part of the office that has to defend the interests of consumers and above all to take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: “Overseas where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephony services.”
But, of course, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is on its own.
Just as the same price of gasoline for all gas stations is certainly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
“The section has found no evidence of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No trader has a dominant position, so it has no corresponding greater responsibility for its market behavior.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecommunications regulator,” Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many controversial points.
Of course, there is the analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, no Czech trader has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach – for the creation of a virtual operator it is always necessary the agreement of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has, logically, the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a minimum warning that three mobile operators proceed in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints by interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS is kept out of the whole thing.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recent update of the Telecommunications Act, despite the fact that many experts expected the situation to improve.
This fact the representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it when no one is looking
While without us noticing it, the operation of these pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are even some in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile telephony services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
