The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar pre-sale.
"If there were the cases you are talking about, which we will be interested in, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions, and could result in the conclusion of cooperation with such a company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> replied to the question in question.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 mentioned companies it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the business of these companies they make a non-indifferent profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: "The law allows for such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
These must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the usual customers of mobile operators "
But this should be a strange minimum at <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another question opens up for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want you will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be more expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually every country where operators were born, traditional operators were more or less trying to prevent their creation.
The topics they used were virtually identical - too small market, too saturated limit, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in developed countries precisely in these cases, regulators intervened to defend not mobile operators but their customers.
Both with formal measures and non-formal pressure, then came to the creation of the first virtual operator and he got others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies throw from one to the other the whole case like a boiling potato.
In our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
