"It was full of rubbish, flakes of clothes and pieces of barrels, posters, leaves, strings."
Some residents, including some bloggers who write of East Village’s “gentrification,” have opposed the idea of selling Extra Place, citing that the piece of public property, modest as it is, should remain public.
Others praised Extra Place as a rarity – a fragment of town for almost nothing changed that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who has a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitled, "The Book of Complaints: A Slightly Nostalgic Look at the Enduring City"), published part of a City History Speech that appeared on The New Yorker in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a sluggish street with no way out, dark even in the daytime and bordered doorways of rusty iron warehouses and windows with snails, with week-old newspapers rolling along the bottoms."
With a few exceptions, the road seemed almost the same as a recent evening.
A rat ran agilely through the back of the road near a door leading inside the CBGB, which is now the site of an aristocratic clothing store.
On the walls were graffiti and an empty 22-ounce beer bottle lying next to a group of abandoned fresh newspapers.
Few passers-by have said that they rarely thought of Extra Place but suggest that it would need to be a little bit beautified.
Mr. Fields, for his part, said that he also thinks some people underestimate the attraction of the road in its current state.
"The best years of my life," he said, "were in dark, dirty, disgusting places."
The bilingual debate: immersion in English
In this essay, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the position of candidates on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a senior member of California studies and the senior director of educational studies at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book “Not as good as you think: Why the middle class needs to choose a school.”
To really attract Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s educational projects are a significant example.
Mr. Obama’s campaign notes that, “African-American and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
To combat these shortcomings in achieving the goals, Obama’s educational plan specifically supports, among other things, “transitional bilingual education” for English students.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes classroom teaching of languages other than English, does not take into account his interest in filling the gaps in learning.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in East Los Angeles County.
The school’s students are mostly Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of students, many of whom have recently arrived, are studying English.
But, among fourth graders, an astonishing 100 percent of students took the upper-level test in the 2008 math state exam.
Equally astonishing 93 percent of fourth graders took the expert level test on the art-of-language-English.
This incredible result was achieved using a different ingredient than Mr. Obama’s favorite.
Sixth Street emphasizes rehearsal and exercise, constant assessment of skills and a “no excuse” attitude.
In addition, and it is here that Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the obstructive approach of the school for English students is "full immersion."
The use of English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the context of education.
Ms. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, "We had a fantastic success with a student who just came from Mexico and if you were in class 12 months later you wouldn't have been able to identify which one it was."
"It works," he observed, "it works for us."
Would Obama model a school like Sixth Street Prep to replicate it in other Hispanic-majority schools and with English students?
The school’s findings make the answer to that question very easy, but the education policy in its own party (the National Education Associations is a long-standing supporter of bilingual education) and its own continued support of bilingual education prevent it from predicting Mr. Obama’s response.
While he agrees that immigrants should study English, Obama recently made the subject trivial when he said that people should stop worrying about “only English” legislation.
Instead, he said, "you have to be sure that your children are able to speak Spanish."
If Obama really wants to close these achievement gaps, he should carefully consider the educational models that work rather than despise or trivialize them.
