In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Hidden in the theme park on the outskirts of Orlando, a few miles from the splendour, the noise, the huge, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come into life.
Eatonville, the first all black town incorporated into the country and Zora Neale Hurston's birthplace, is no longer as simple as he described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, abundance of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect for Hurston, the most famous Harlem Renaissance writer.
Yet in many ways, the city he described – and that makes tourists stop by understanding it in Florida’s travel guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project – remains a place apart.
It is as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, that "knowing so little about us, you don't know what you're missing."
Even now, in a year where a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called for an opening speech on the race, many here remain dissatisfied with the look of the outsider.
“We are very careful about how our story is being told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifetime resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
"It must be fair."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black power grab and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shadow of the oaks of the rural culture of the southern blacks - sometimes disdainful, sometimes rewarded - born from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the worry about Eatonville's imagination really started with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of Florida's guide transformed the city, just outside Route 17, a road running through Florida's often-forgotten center within a scenery of black history and human drama.
Low as a mess in both life and literature, Hurston brought readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
"Out of the road to the left," he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white finishes, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could barely read and write."
She also mentioned Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever fits in the passage rooms."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly this wasn't Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora was saying it as it was," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girls who Hurston immortalized her by quoting men singing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds, "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who often returned from his family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that when Hurston was raining in the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts decent clothing today.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin says, while others were sniffing.
“People were always very happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin said.
But, he added, waving on his patio chair on the back overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston most likely was baptized, "she never stayed long".
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten it.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a plaque-free grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no major commemorative ceremonies, and no major conference.
"I don't think they understand her contribution to the world or her legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of Wrapped in Rainbows, a Hurston biography published in 2003.
A change took place in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-lane highway.
Orlando's expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 across the city's western boundary.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relative idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the front door of the community.
“During that period, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and stuff to the people sitting on one side,” says Mr. Franklin.
“In fact, we had a girl who was killed by that once.
They threw a cockroach out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, defining his Brown decision against the school office as "an insult rather than an honor to my race".
Residents now say that the disintegration of schools, despite having been positive in some respects, dilutes Eatonville’s cohesion and threatens the confidence of its youth.
“Black children were used to being embraced — I remember this — hugging your teacher in the morning, hugging your teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, the daughter of Ella Dinkins and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a non-profit group.
This lasted, he added, until teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't embrace your white teacher because your white teacher... - I mean, there's a cultural division there," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped and created space for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudices, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines like: "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I can't really understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker embarked on a long journey to Hurston's unmarked tomb and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway hit bookstore shelves, reintroducing it back into the American canon.
The project of the highway came just as his most famous daughter had turned the lights on the sidewalk again.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a saviour.
The community began designing a festival dedicated to Hurston in 1988 to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state withdrew from its road project.
“The five lanes of the resuscitated highway brought what would be called high speed, a real pride for the city,” Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd makes it simpler: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped change the city’s image of itself.
Outsiders like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the public historical register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (called as Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a repainted and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the sensation of a secondary road under summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
(It’s 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to search for the history of Eatonville, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A pre-requested permission is required for most of the interviews, to some things — like the murals on Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man, who show black men in the fields — do not have permission to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a fat teacher, with a weak for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as soon as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of citizen pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing her entire race: beautiful, problems and everything, neither better, nor worse and proud, creative, great worker, stupid and confused as other races and ethnic groups in America.
It’s heartfelt civic affection what can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s grandson, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, who he said may need help.
And even those who are younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“A lot of people, if they’ve just come in here, will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'” said Alondra Kenon after mass on a recent Sunday.
“But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it’s really a pretty city.”
