"I photograph the master away from the scene to extract his character" Günther Bauer, photographer
No heels, no steering wheel, no clothes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the interpretation, to look at the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Two inseparable faces, except in the private, in those moments far from the public, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they do not have to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots to singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the lesser-known side of these masters.
With this lens, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, taking it from different angles of view.
The exhibition, included in the program of the Flamenco Photography Month, reflects the international importance of this dance, every day increasing," explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" it could also be ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists.
These people portrayed "on the street" are "artists capable of transmitting passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and capturing the audience.
To capture the personality of these great men you do not need to portray them on the scene,
because their personality and character are internal.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera the personality of the great flamenco.”
With a passion for the festival "Cante de las Minas", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey aimed at portraying singers, guitarists or dancers using a ballet camera.
They are portraits that, because of the type of machine and the material, remember the classic photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of image, conferring on the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects the conception of Bauer's own flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day."
Not the dance, the singing or the playing itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, able to conquer the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the El Photomata gallery.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are included in this selection of about seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a kind of flamenco anthology, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited during the exhibition.
The passion for portraiture led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of veteran athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits "I love to portray people, know them and be able to penetrate for a moment in their lives, whether this is a long or short moment.
I think portrait is the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or compare with people, characters you sometimes don’t even know or who give you just a few minutes to take a picture.
Beyond these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to put my ideas into practice.”
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people" is set up at the gallery El Photomata, at number 20 on Via de la Mata, parallel to Via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until next 16 October.
