Talking in your sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who talk while sleeping.
The first time it happens, at the most you take a scare, but in reality it doesn’t matter much.
This is a benign alteration of sleep called sleepwalking.
It manifests itself with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Certainly, most of you have been told that you spoke in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the baby remembers nothing.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime enuresis (doing the piss in bed), or sleepwalking, but that is not necessarily the case.
As already mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stressful situations, or stressful situations.
In any case, it is a phenomenon still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper, or the opposite happens (crying, screaming, long speeches...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a way out of the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stress situation).
What can be done, however, is to consider a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to bed.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or TV shows that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiresome to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more calmly.
Once the sleepers appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless, because he's not aware of what's going on, and you're gonna stop him from sleeping.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if it appears very anxious and the episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check where such great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common situation), don’t fall into the temptation to ask him for information.
You will not get anything, because he is asleep and therefore unconscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what it says but not see what it is dreaming to say, so you need to pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions it could lead to.
Never tell your child that you can ask them questions at night to know their secrets.
Not even for a joke.
Such a thing causes a great deal of distress.
In short, don’t worry, it’s nothing serious, it’s an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
