The meeting - The blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the infected blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
Faced with such a drama and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the re-proposal of a disaster.
While Judge Krever was late to draw up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) to all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the Québec donation system, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to the ongoing efforts to improve the safety of blood collections and field research over the following years, we have regained the public’s trust”, he explains before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Héma-c.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, says the one who has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we did not know at all whether that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It is therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when you have doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, take measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was rejected.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that this disease is no doubt transmitted through infected blood.
This episode so proved to us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow to recognize the presence of the virus in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, that is, from the moment the person contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to a duration of less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them is thus greatly reduced.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood infected with the HIV virus.
In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years for a case of HIV transmitted by transfusion to occur.
I believe that today one can feel at ease in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to regain health, says the head of the management of the Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
You have to be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continues before stressing that in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
“Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Being the most aggressive cancer treatments, patients often need an intake of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the number of donors that on average make up only 3% of Quebec residents acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who have reached the age of 18 and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where it is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Cases of deficiency are very rare.
But we must renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that it is hardly an hour to donate blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eyeball heart valves, and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at the Héma-Québec which manages the only public navel cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, plenty of blood rich in stem cells that can serve to cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the inclusion in the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
You should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Décary who describes this practice of taking cord blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to you," as Héma-Québec does not have the necessary means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Québec.
