The Psychology of Excessive Bidding: Why Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers are likely to spend more, to overvalue the goods.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have managed to discover the neuro-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, men do not want to stay behind in a race such as the eBay auction, so they are willing to pay a higher price.
Research has sought to trace the nervous pattern of this "game" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lot, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active areas of the brains of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games the participants could win money, but in the game of the auction, where the essential element is to bid more than the other, the body striat under the cerebral cortex enters intensively when it loses to the game.
This area of the brain, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-gratification" of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in price is explained by scanning the vehement reaction of the striped body.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group conducted a financial follow-up survey.
In this investigation, three groups bid against a partner in different conditions.
They reported to the control group what the actual value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
To another group besides this they promised that in case of winning they would receive another prize of $15.
The third group would have received $15 before the auction, but the group members would have lost money in the event of a loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that for one of them the win was highlighted, and for the other the loss.
By testing the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the group who played "against the loss" were willing to make higher bets than the control group or "winner".
“These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, these so far explained the phenomena encountered at the auctions with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image have helped resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so we have come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of New York School of Economics.
Hepatitis: When to go to the doctor?
Nearly half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, but in Hungary chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7000 are cured: the reason is that many patients do not know that they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and iteration, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g., water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal leaks, saliva).
For those traveling, it is useful to vaccinate against viruses A and B, there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After the formation of yellowish spots on the skin and white of the eyes, the feces become clear and the urine dark, the healing takes place within two to three weeks.
A million people die every year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooists.
In the world today, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Because even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease is worth talking to a family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by disease associations around the world.
The purpose is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and the early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the results of a recent investigation, religious faith works as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God influences the sensation of pain, the British Telegraph said.
As part of the somewhat bizarre investigation an electroshock was carried out to 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists, while all of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first in a series of research in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University take part.
The test was carried out exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the seventeenth century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci's hermelin painted in the fifteenth century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would give rise to some sort of religious status among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and considered it to be a reassuring effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time loop received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
The Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "someone took care" of them and "they were calmed down and they were pervaded by peace".
Looking at the religious-themed image they realized 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that a similar result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but it is necessary to find the appropriate image.
“We need to look for an image that has very positive feelings, like a mother or a father,” he said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the results of the search.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it manages to change our personality,” Wright added.
After the excellent results, only the question remains whether the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar calibre is presented to the believers, what effect could it have on pain control?
Would the vision of a Virgin Mary of quality bring better results?
