The intelligent machine mimics the flight of the cockroach
What could be the best way to develop anti-collision technologies if not to imitate the sensors of obstacles found in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the astonishing project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the calabrons gave Nissan engineers the initial strategic impetus on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic mini-car with bee properties, with the ultimate goal of creating a system capable of scanning all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that really looks a lot like our protective shield - explained to the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR and R&D technologies.
Important is the role of the bee's view, capable of a view of 300 degrees in each direction.
The engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee's view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, mimicking the bee's movements, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the necessary measure to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, unlike the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
"If this were not the case, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions," said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place at a glance.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steerability of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, speed up and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, lighter and high energy density, which means that their life is longer than lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantaneity of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even the ability to store it.
This robot must process some input in a few seconds and react.
No need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it only uses a few dozen Kb of memory.
There is no need for a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, Nissan expects, within 10 years, can be installed on standard vehicles.
Further possibility of application can be represented by unification with the GPS satellite navigation system which avoiding the obstacles present on the road leads to the destination.
