Mp3 Players Under Accusation, Put Hearing at Risk
Listening to high-volume music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing loss.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a communiqué circulated in Brussels quotes the opinion of the EU Scientific Committee on Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risks (Csrseri) published today.
"From this scientific opinion - read the note - it turns out that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices for more than an hour a day holding the device high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability."
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and high-sounding cell phones can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably,” says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings, a clear risk emerges, and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is that we need to raise awareness among consumers and make this information public.
We also need to review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology.”
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical instruments and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise caused by them.
"Scientists confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine, together with Member States and stakeholders, what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical instruments and appliances."
At present, there is already a European safety standard limiting the noise level of portable musical equipment to 100 dB, but concerns are growing about hearing damage that may result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
You can limit these damage greatly by using solutions such as reducing noise levels and exposure duration.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable musical equipment if they listen to high-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for just 5 hours per week exceed the currently applicable limits for maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in these conditions for longer periods of time are at risk of permanent hearing loss after a period of 5 years.
This would apply to 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
