The Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already manifested a few days ago with the House vote against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by the New York Times yesterday informing us that the current crisis is tearing apart the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, strong, conservative, hostile to "the Center of the States" and to the world of finance.
The soul, by the way, which has become overwhelmingly alive with the vote I said at the beginning.
But this is just an example of the changes, of the great changes, which the ongoing economic earthquake perhaps foreshadows or already lets us see: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here alone.
Both in the U.S. and Europe, the crisis seems to work as an accelerator of long-time incubation phenomena that in the new climate are solidifying and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the double category of State-sovereignty in relation to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that, yes, have close ties with abroad, but first of all see the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
Which immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially out of the question or to have little to say: the shining proof is given by the European Union, which as usual is divided between the different interests and between the different state strategies is unable to decide any common policy line.
And so it is from the government of each individual state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and relaunch plans, new rules, and above all the dispensing of funds: since when it comes to the tights it is only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back in place.
And they also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which probably no market and no international organization can ever have to the same extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that recent economic developments tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had already entered the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the intangible, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized from a point of view that our future, unfortunately, will have to take account of me.
All things that, look a little bit, can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but are nevertheless absolutely connected to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So whoever finds himself to be sovereign, certainly has several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune of living in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty that presages a fracture.
Those who say Territory, State, Government, inevitably say Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis appears to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand of someone who knows how to handle the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, especially economic ones, proved so inadequate and full of shadows.
And together, something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an intolerance, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
That is to say, it seems to be becoming increasingly clearer, in vast sections of the population, that before their actions are the same ideas of the social elites at the moment in the rise, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the general sense of the term, to have made their own time and to be more and more strangers to the outside world.
The demand for leadership, in short, subterraneanly fuels a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and the traditional political set-ups, which manifests itself in the sudden "revolts" of the elections or in the sudden turns of the collective humour of the latter, also with the crocodiles in the last and most recent times.
It has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it more and more difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what it can represent, what is not economically taking shape in the deep layers of societies.
In the face of all this, talking about a “mass rebellion” on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not for nothing.
