Farewell old cinema Paradise, cities erase historic halls
The historic cinemas close in favor of the multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the great Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of the large multi-rooms and the consequent death by consuming the mono-rooms in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that seem inevitable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear are often historical places and loads of memory,"it is as if a friend, a acquaintance with whom we have shared a piece of the road and many emotions", observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago he gave to Tornatore the Oscar award and the Grand Prix of the Jury.
The figures provided by the Anec, the main association of performers, speak clearly: in the last five years have closed the beating 316 cinemas of the traditional type, and paying the biggest price are mainly the halls in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Tor in Rome, 6 less in Rome.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the most number of new multi-sale cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, “it is useful that new structures are being built but the survival of existing ones should be guaranteed, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move to the multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of appropriation for the fund in favour of the executors: the debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the government does not respect existing laws.
It would require between 16 and 18 million euros a year to support the sector.”
Interestingly, the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, decided to run for repairs with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote monosale cinemas both in the historic center and in the outskirts.
The rules include tax facilitation measures in favour of operators and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for the stop and in some parking lots.
“It’s an initiative that I like,” observes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is true, however, that to counteract the overpowering of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the audience today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "New Cinema Paradise", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, so as not to see the dusty posters I turn on the other side.
