When energy arises from the waves now come down into the field the big
It is an inexhaustible field, which occupies over 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have set their eyes, and now they are trying to put their hands, colossal like the Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmentalist instances and the new rise in oil give the sector a boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore wave-moving plants.
That would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
Colossians at the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in the north of Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away, we are betting on marine energy more and more and among these companies have always voted for traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying technologies on ocean energy,” a spokesperson for a U.S. oil giant company told the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining permission from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It’s a not-so-significant signal, especially if you consider that it is in Alaska that the U.S. continues to extract oil, and President Bush recently launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, there are New York’s Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey’s Ocean Power to walk the path of energy coming from the sea and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, according to the observers, indicate an interest in the rise.
Technology to be put in place.
Experts are talking about a technology still at dawn, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
In order to produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: the Ocean Power, for example, uses a boe system connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which causes the boobs to move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure causes a turbine to rotate, which in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now, there are four such plants under construction, waiting only for federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping mall and parking using six underwater turbines in the East River in New York.
The movement of water when there are tides causes the blades of the turbines to rotate, creating a rotational movement that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permissions to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they tell the Institute for Electricity Research, deserves the potential of the tides right now.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that were like that of New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others that overlook the coast, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and expected investments up to 35 million by 2009.
